## [1] "At threshold of HPEs<1, 90%ile of measured error (m) of sync/ref positions = 10.61"
## [1] "At threshold of HPEs<1, 83.27% of sync/ref positions retained"
  • Based on these graphics I lean towards using an HPE filtering threshold of HPE=1; this seems to be a nice tradeoff between precision (mean = 6m in HPE bin 0.75-1) and quantity of data (~80% of data retained).

  • After incorporating the later three releases at higher flows, it seems that eprhaps a threshold of HPE<0.5 is more suitable for the following reasons:

  • In the Fremont 2015 report we used an HPE of 0.5: this retained 52.8% of the positions, with a median of 144 detections per fish. Vemco estimated that this threshold (in 2015) resulted in 50% fish positions had error less than 1.21m, while 95% of positions had error <4.17m (90%ile was 2.84m).

  • The vemco reports are a little more difficult to interpret in 2016 because they were completed in two rounds. For release 1&2, at HPE<0.5 68% of fish positions were retained, and 50% had errors < 1.57m while 95% had errors < 4.62. This is more comparable to 2015 than using a threshold of HPE<1 (50% = 1.68, 95% = 5.86). However, for releases 3, 4, & 5, at HPE<0.5 64% of positions are retained (similar), yet the errors go up (much higher flows). 50% had errors < 2.04, 95% had errors < 10.74, and 90% had errors < 7.24. Here is an excerpt from VEMCOs results document for releases 1 & 2 that is returned with the post-processed VPS dataset, regarding thier estimate of the precision of the fish positions:

Fish tag precision is estimated here using a simple method of comparing pairs of calculated positions that are very close in time, based on the knowledge that over a short period of time a fish will travel a relatively short distance. The time durations between successive transmissions of a fish tag in this study follow a pseudorandom sequence, with a minimum of 1.0 seconds, a maximum of 2.0 seconds, and an average of 1.5 seconds. For each of the HPEs filters, the retained positions are analyzed as follows: Pairs of positions from the same transmitter that are within 2.0 seconds of each other are identified, and the horizontal distances between these pairs of positions are calculated Selected percentiles of these horizontal distances are calculated The following is a summary of these analyses: HPEs # Pos % pos 50%ile 80%ile 90%ile 95%ile 0.2 25792 21% 1.34 2.04 2.56 3.16 0.5 83658 68% 1.57 2.54 3.45 4.62 1.0 106529 87% 1.68 2.93 4.21 5.86 For example, using an HPEs filter of 1.0, half of the pairs of calculated positions that are within 2.0 seconds of each other are less than 1.68 metres apart, and 80% are within 2.93m. Note that these statistics cannot be compared directly with the corresponding statistics for sync and reference tags because they include a component based on an average of 1.5 seconds of fish motion.

And the numbers from VEMCOs results document for releases 3, 4, & 5: > The following is a summary of these analyses: > HPEs # Pos % pos 50%ile 80%ile 90%ile 95%ile > 0.2 4527 13% 1.83 3.36 5.00 6.59 > 0.5 21054 64% 2.04 4.58 7.24 10.74 > 1.0 28279 86% 2.22 5.49 9.03 13.39 For example, using an HPEs filter of 1.0, half of the pairs of calculated positions that are within 2.0 seconds of each other are less than 2.22 metres apart, and 80% are within 5.49m. ***
